      title: "Discontinuous Measurement: Tradeoffs and Appropriate Use",
      body: "Discontinuous measurement methods sacrifice precision for practicality. They do not record every instance of behavior — they sample behavior across time and use that sample to estimate overall occurrence. The BCBA exam tests not just your ability to define these methods but to predict the direction of their error and identify when each is justified.\n\nPartial-interval recording (PIR) scores an interval as positive if the behavior occurs at any point during it — even for a fraction of a second. A behavior lasting one second in a 30-second interval receives the same score as one lasting the full 30 seconds. The result is systematic overestimation of behavioral prevalence. PIR is most appropriate for brief, high-frequency behaviors where capturing every instance via continuous recording is impractical.\n\nWhole-interval recording (WIR) scores an interval as positive only if the behavior persists throughout the entire interval. This produces systematic underestimation — any behavior that starts and stops within the interval goes unscored. WIR is best suited to measuring sustained behavioral states, such as on-task behavior or engagement, where the clinical concern is whether the behavior is maintained continuously.\n\nMomentary time sampling (MTS) observes the client only at the precise moment the interval ends, not during it. It is the most accurate of the three discontinuous methods, particularly when intervals are kept short relative to behavior duration. Powell, Martindale, and Kulp (1975) demonstrated empirically that MTS accuracy converges toward continuous measurement as interval length decreases — a finding with direct implications for how interval timers should be calibrated in practice.\n\nA critical exam point: discontinuous methods are second-best options justified only when continuous measurement is genuinely impractical. They are not equivalent alternatives — they introduce known, predictable error that must be acknowledged in clinical documentation."
