      body: "Interobserver agreement (IOA) is the primary mechanism by which behavioral measurement validity is monitored in applied settings. It quantifies the degree to which two independent observers produce equivalent data when observing the same behavior during the same period. IOA is not a measure of observer accuracy in an absolute sense — it is a measure of consistency between observers — but consistent disagreement between observers is the primary detectable signal that measurement is breaking down.\n\nTotal count IOA: Divide the smaller frequency count by the larger and multiply by 100. Simple and commonly used, but can be misleadingly high when behavior rates are elevated — two observers can agree on total count while disagreeing entirely on which instances were counted.\n\nExact count per interval IOA: Compare observer counts interval by interval; score each interval as agreement only when counts match exactly. More stringent and more informative than total count IOA.\n\nPartial agreement per interval: Award partial credit when counts within an interval differ. More sensitive to the degree of disagreement than exact count methods.\n\nOccurrence and non-occurrence IOA: Calculate agreement separately for intervals in which behavior occurred and intervals in which it did not. This is critical when behavior rate is very high or very low — overall IOA can appear acceptable while one of these categories is actually quite poor. The BACB recommends reporting both.\n\nAcceptable IOA is generally defined as 80% or above, with 90% preferred for publication-quality data. The exam will present IOA calculations and ask you to evaluate whether the data meets acceptable standards."
