      body: "Validity in experimental design refers to the accuracy of inferences drawn from data. Two distinct types of validity bear directly on the BCBA exam and on how behavior analysts evaluate and design research.\n\nInternal validity is the degree to which observed changes in the DV can be confidently attributed to the IV rather than to extraneous variables. A study has high internal validity when the experimental design effectively rules out alternative explanations — history effects, maturation, testing effects, instrumentation changes, and regression to the mean. Single-case designs achieve internal validity through systematic replication: demonstrating that behavior changes when the IV is introduced and returns toward baseline when it is withdrawn, or that the same effect appears across multiple tiers when the IV is introduced sequentially.\n\nExternal validity is the degree to which experimental findings generalize beyond the specific conditions of the study — to other subjects, settings, behaviors, and time periods. Single-case research has historically been critiqued for limited external validity because findings are demonstrated with individual subjects. The behavior-analytic response to this critique, articulated most clearly by Sidman (1960), is that replication across subjects and settings — both direct and systematic — is the appropriate mechanism for establishing generality, not statistical inference from group averages.\n\nThe exam will present scenarios and ask you to identify which type of validity is threatened and why. Common internal validity threats include concurrent changes in the environment during a study phase, and common external validity limitations include demonstration with only one subject in one setting."
